description:
When using $set with dot notation like { "$set": { "profile.level": 2 } }, MongoLake incorrectly creates a top-level key 'profile.level' instead of updating the nested field at profile.level. This was discovered by the dual-run compatibility tests comparing MongoLake output against MongoDB.

Example:
- Input doc: { _id: 'nested-update', profile: { name: 'Test', level: 1 } }
- Update: { $set: { 'profile.level': 2, 'profile.badge': 'gold' } }
- Expected: { _id: 'nested-update', profile: { name: 'Test', level: 2, badge: 'gold' } }
- Actual: { _id: 'nested-update', profile: { name: 'Test', level: 1 }, 'profile.level': 2, 'profile.badge': 'gold' }

The fix should be in src/client/collection.ts where update operators are processed. Need to parse dot notation paths and traverse/create nested objects accordingly.
